 <subsection xml:id="subsec-The-net-of-a-cylinder">
        <title>The net of a cylinder</title>
        <p>
            In the previous section, you identified a cylinder. Discuss what to look for when identifying a cylinder.
        </p>

        <p>
            In this section, you will sketch nets of a cylinder.
        </p>
        <activity>
            <title></title>
            <statement>

                <p>
                    <m>\textbf{Work in pairs}</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <term>What you need:</term>  model of a cylinder and a pair of scissors (or a cutting tool).
                </p>

                <p>
                    <ol>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                (a).Take a close look at a cylinder model similar to the one shown below.
                            </p>
                            <image width="50%">
                                <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                                <latex-image label="cylindr1">
                                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                                    % Define colors
                                    \definecolor{myblue1}{rgb}{0.2, 0.6, 1.0}   % Blue for top and bottom ellipses
                                    \definecolor{myblue2}{rgb}{0.2, 0.3, 0.8}   % Darker blue for curved surface
                                    
                                    % Draw the bottom ellipse
                                    \shade[bottom color=myblue1, top color=white, opacity=0.5] (0,0) ellipse (2 and 0.5);
                                    \draw[thick, black] (0,0) ellipse (2 and 0.5);
                                    
                                    % Draw the curved surface in blue
                                    \filldraw[bottom color=myblue2, top color=white, opacity=0.5] (-2,0) -- (-2,4) arc (180:360:2 and 0.5) -- (2,0) -- cycle;
                                    \draw[thick, black] (-2,0) -- (-2,4);
                                    \draw[thick, black] (2,0) -- (2,4);
                                    
                                    % Draw the top ellipse
                                    \shade[bottom color=myblue1, top color=white, opacity=0.5] (0,4) ellipse (2 and 0.5);
                                    \draw[thick, black] (0,4) ellipse (2 and 0.5);
                                    \end{tikzpicture}
                                </latex-image>
                                
                            </image>

                            <p>
                                (b). Can you find any flat surfaces, curved surfaces, edges, or vertices?
                            </p>
                        </li>

                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Carefully cut the cylinder along its side and base.
                            </p>
                        </li>

                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Gently unfold the shape and lay it flat on your desk.
                            </p>
                        </li>

                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Observe the flattened shape and draw what you see.
                            </p>
                        </li>

                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Identify and label the shapes that make up the cylinder when opened out.
                            </p>
                        </li>

                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Share and compare your diagrams with those from other groups. What similarities or differences can you see?
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>

            </statement>
        </activity>

        <p>
                    <m>\textbf{Key Takeaway}</m>
                </p>

                <p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                    A cylinder has 3 faces. Two faces are circles and one face is a rectangle. A net of a cylinder is made up of 2 circles and 1 rectangle.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                A closed cylinder includes two circular ends and one curved side.
                            </p>
                        </li>

                        <li>
                            <p>
                                An open cylinder has only one circular end and the curved surface.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </p>

        <p>
        <m>\textbf{To observe the net of a cylinder.}</m>
        </p>
            <figure>
                <caption></caption>
                <interactive xml:id="geogebra-cylinde" geogebra="eevymk37" width="100%" aspect="9:5" reset-icon="yes" />
            </figure>

            <example>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Sketch the net of the cylinder given below.
                    </p>

                    <image width="50%">
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                            % Define colors
                            \definecolor{myorange}{rgb}{1.0, 0.6, 0.2}  % Orange color for top and bottom
                            \definecolor{myred}{rgb}{1.0, 0.2, 0.2}     % Red color for curved surface

                            % Draw the bottom ellipse
                            \shade[bottom color=myorange, top color=white, opacity=0.5] (0,0) ellipse (2 and 0.5);
                            \draw[thick, black] (0,0) ellipse (2 and 0.5);

                            % Draw the curved surface in red
                            \filldraw[bottom color=myred, top color=white, opacity=0.5] (-2,0) -- (-2,4) arc (180:360:2 and 0.5) -- (2,0) -- cycle;
                            \draw[thick, black] (-2,0) -- (-2,4);
                            \draw[thick, black] (2,0) -- (2,4);

                            % Draw the top ellipse
                            \shade[bottom color=myorange, top color=white, opacity=0.5] (0,4) ellipse (2 and 0.5);
                            \draw[thick, black] (0,4) ellipse (2 and 0.5);

                            % Radius annotation
                            \draw[dashed] (0,4) -- (2,4);
                            \node[right] at (0.8,4.1) {\small $14 cm$};

                            % Height annotation
                            \draw[dashed] (0,0) -- (0,4);
                            \node[right] at (0,2) {\small $15 cm$};
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                        <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                        
                    </image>
                </statement>

                <solution>
                    <p>
                        The net of the cylinder is shown below.
                    </p>
                    <image width="50%">
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                            % Define colors
                            \definecolor{myorange}{rgb}{1.0, 0.6, 0.2}  % Orange for circular bases
                            \definecolor{myred}{rgb}{0.8, 0.2, 0.4}     % Red for the rectangle

                            % Draw the rectangular surface of the cylinder
                            \filldraw[fill=myred, draw=black, thick] (-3,-2) rectangle (3,2);

                            % Draw the two circular bases
                            \filldraw[fill=myorange, draw=black, thick] (0,3.5) circle (1.5);
                            \filldraw[fill=myorange, draw=black, thick] (0,-3.5) circle (1.5);

                            % Draw dashed lines to indicate radius and height
                        
                            \node[right] at (3,0) {\small $15 cm$};
                            
                            \draw[dashed] (0,3.6) -- (1.5,3.6);
                            \draw[dashed] (0,-3.6) -- (1.5,-3.6);
                            \node[right] at (0.4,3.8) {\small $14 cm$};
                            \node[right] at (0.4,-3.8) {\small $14 cm$};
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                        <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                        
                    </image>
                </solution>
            </example>
        
    </subsection>